2. MVC (Model-View-Controller) Design Pattern ğŸ›ï¸
ğŸ§  Logic:The Model-View-Controller (MVC) is a foundational $\mathbf{architectural~design~pattern}$ used to develop UIs (User Interfaces) by separating an application into three interconnected parts. This pattern aims to isolate development complexity, making code easier to maintain and reuse.Model: Manages the $\mathbf{data}$ and $\mathbf{business~logic}$ of the application (e.g., interacting with the database using JPA/Hibernate).View: Handles the $\mathbf{presentation}$ of the data to the user (e.g., using $\mathbf{JSP}$ or HTML).Controller: Acts as an $\mathbf{intermediary}$ that processes user input, updates the Model, and selects the appropriate View to display the result (e.g., using a $\mathbf{Servlet}$).ğŸ“Œ Example (Web Request Flow):1. Client Request (Browser) -> 
2. **Controller** (Servlet) receives request.
3. Controller asks **Model** (Java classes/DAO) to fetch/update data.
4. Model returns data to Controller.
5. Controller selects **View** (JSP) and passes data to it.
6. View renders HTML using the data.
7. HTML Response -> Client.
